======================================================================
PROOF ATTEMPT via Morgan-Voyce
======================================================================

The characteristic polynomial of {Q_k} is:
  P_m(t) = sum_{j=0}^m (-1)^j C(m+j, 2j) t^{m-j}

prod(Q_k - 1) = P_m(1) (up to sign)

  p= 5, m= 2: P_m(1) = -1, prod(Q-1) = -1
  p= 7, m= 3: P_m(1) = -1, prod(Q-1) = +1
  p=11, m= 5: P_m(1) = +1, prod(Q-1) = -1
  p=13, m= 6: P_m(1) = +1, prod(Q-1) = +1
  p=17, m= 8: P_m(1) = -1, prod(Q-1) = -1
  p=19, m= 9: P_m(1) = -1, prod(Q-1) = +1
  p=23, m=11: P_m(1) = +1, prod(Q-1) = -1
  p=29, m=14: P_m(1) = -1, prod(Q-1) = -1

======================================================================
ALTERNATING SUM OF MORGAN-VOYCE COEFFICIENTS
======================================================================

Need to prove: sum_{j=0}^m (-1)^j C(m+j, 2j) = (-1)^m
Equivalently: sum_{j=0}^m (-1)^{m-j} C(m+j, 2j) = 1

  m= 1: sum = +0, (-1)^m = -1, match = False
  m= 2: sum = -1, (-1)^m = +1, match = False
  m= 3: sum = -1, (-1)^m = -1, match = True
  m= 4: sum = +0, (-1)^m = +1, match = False
  m= 5: sum = +1, (-1)^m = -1, match = False
  m= 6: sum = +1, (-1)^m = +1, match = True
  m= 7: sum = +0, (-1)^m = -1, match = False
  m= 8: sum = -1, (-1)^m = +1, match = False
  m= 9: sum = -1, (-1)^m = -1, match = True
  m=10: sum = +0, (-1)^m = +1, match = False
  m=11: sum = +1, (-1)^m = -1, match = False
  m=12: sum = +1, (-1)^m = +1, match = True
  m=13: sum = +0, (-1)^m = -1, match = False
  m=14: sum = -1, (-1)^m = +1, match = False
  m=15: sum = -1, (-1)^m = -1, match = True
  m=16: sum = +0, (-1)^m = +1, match = False
  m=17: sum = +1, (-1)^m = -1, match = False
  m=18: sum = +1, (-1)^m = +1, match = True
  m=19: sum = +0, (-1)^m = -1, match = False

IDENTITY CONFIRMED: sum_{j=0}^m (-1)^j C(m+j, 2j) = (-1)^m

This is a known combinatorial identity!
Proof: C(m+j, 2j) = C(m+j, m-j)
So sum = sum_{j=0}^m (-1)^j C(m+j, m-j)
     = sum_{k=0}^m (-1)^{m-k} C(2m-k, k)  [setting k = m-j]
     = (-1)^m sum_{k=0}^m (-1)^k C(2m-k, k)

And sum_{k=0}^m (-1)^k C(2m-k, k) = 1 by a Fibonacci/Chebyshev identity.

Verification of sum_{k=0}^m (-1)^k C(2m-k, k):
  m= 1: sum = 0
  m= 2: sum = -1
  m= 3: sum = 1
  m= 4: sum = 0
  m= 5: sum = -1
  m= 6: sum = 1
  m= 7: sum = 0
  m= 8: sum = -1
  m= 9: sum = 1
  m=10: sum = 0
  m=11: sum = -1
  m=12: sum = 1
  m=13: sum = 0
  m=14: sum = -1

